Sample Codes

Netflix Data

1. Download the netflix_titles at this link. Create a century variable taking two values:

- '21' if the released_year is greater or equal to 2000, and

- '20' otherwise. 
library(tidyverse)
library(tidytext)
library(knitr)
df <- readr::read_csv('netflix_titles.csv')
df$century <- ifelse(df$release_year>=2000,'21','20')

2. Word Frequency

  1. Convert the description to tokens, remove all the stop words. What are the top 10 frequent words of movies/TV Shows in the 20th century. Plot the bar chart of the frequency of these words.
df %>% filter(century=='20') %>% 
  unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% 
  anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
  count(type, word, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  head(10) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = n, y = reorder(word, n))) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(y = '', x = 'Frequency')

  1. What are the top 10 frequent words of movies/TV Shows in the 21st century. Plot the bar chart of the frequency of these words. Plot a side-by-side bar charts to compare the most frequent words by the two centuries.
df %>%
  unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% 
  anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
  count(century, word, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  group_by(century) %>%
  slice_max(n, n = 10) %>% 
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(word = reorder_within(word, by = n, within = century)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(n, word, fill = century)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~century, scales = "free") +
  labs(x = "Frequency",
       y = NULL)+
  scale_y_reordered()

3. Word Cloud

  1. Plot the word cloud of the words in the descriptions in the movies/TV Shows in the 20th century.
library(wordcloud) 
pal <- brewer.pal(8,"Dark2")

df %>%filter(century=='20')%>% unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% 
  anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
  count(word, sort = TRUE) %>%
  with(wordcloud(word, n, random.order = FALSE, max.words = 50, colors=pal))

  1. Plot the word cloud of the words in the descriptions in the movies/TV Shows in the 21st century.
df %>%filter(century=='21')%>% unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% 
  anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
  count(word, sort = TRUE) %>%
  with(wordcloud(word, n, random.order = FALSE, max.words = 50, colors=pal))

4. Sentiment Analysis

  1. Is movies/TV Shows in the 21st century tends to be more positive than those in 20th century? Use the sentiment analysis by Bing lexicons to address the question.
df %>%
    unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% 
    anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
    count(century, word, sort = TRUE) %>%
    group_by(century) %>% 
    inner_join(get_sentiments("bing")) %>%
    filter(!is.na(sentiment)) %>%
    count(sentiment, sort = TRUE) %>% 
    group_by(century) %>% 
    mutate(n = n/sum(n)) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(century, n, fill=sentiment))+geom_col(position = 'fill')+
    labs(y='Relative Frequency', x ='')

  1. Do sentiment analysis using nrc and afinn lexicons. Give your comments on the results.
library(textdata)
df %>%
    unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% 
    anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
    count(century, word, sort = TRUE) %>%
    group_by(century) %>% 
    inner_join(get_sentiments("nrc")) %>%
    filter(!is.na(sentiment)) %>%
    count(sentiment, sort = TRUE) %>% 
    group_by(century) %>% 
    mutate(n = n/sum(n)) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(century, n, fill=sentiment))+geom_col(position = 'fill')+
    labs(y='Relative Frequency', x ='')

df %>%
    unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% 
    anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
    count(century, word, sort = TRUE) %>%
    group_by(century) %>% 
    inner_join(get_sentiments("afinn")) %>%
    mutate(sentiment = value) %>% 
    filter(!is.na(sentiment)) %>%
    count(sentiment, sort = TRUE) %>% 
    group_by(century) %>% 
    mutate(n = n/sum(n)) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(sentiment, n, fill= century))+geom_col(position = 'dodge')+
    labs(y='Relative Frequency', x ='')

5. Modeling

  1. Use the description to predict if a movie/TV show is in 20th or 21st century. Give the accuracy and plot the confusion matrix table.
library(caret)
library(themis)
library(textrecipes)

df <- df %>% 
  mutate(target = century) %>% 
  select(target, description) 

a <- recipe(target~description,
       data = df) %>% 
  step_tokenize(description) %>% 
  step_tokenfilter(description, max_tokens = 50) %>% 
  step_tfidf(description) %>% 
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% 
  step_smote(target) %>% 
  prep()
df <- juice(a)

set.seed(2021)
splitIndex <- createDataPartition(df$target, p = .10, 
                                  list = FALSE)
df_train <- df[ splitIndex,]
df_test <- df[-splitIndex,]

forest_ranger <- train(target~., data=df_train, 
                        method = "ranger")

pred <- predict(forest_ranger, df_test)

cm <- confusionMatrix(data = pred, reference = df_test$target)
cm$overall[1]
## Accuracy 
## 0.904679
d = data.frame(pred = pred, obs = df_test$target)
library(yardstick)
d %>% conf_mat(pred, obs) %>% autoplot

  1. Create variable century2 taking three following values. (Hint: You can use the case_when function to do this)
- `21` if released_year is greater or equal to 2000

- `second_half_20`if released_year is greater than or equal to 1950 and less than 2000

- `first_half_20` otherwise
d1 <- readr::read_csv('netflix_titles.csv')
d1$century <- ifelse(d1$release_year>=2000,'21','20')
d1$century2 <- case_when(d1$release_year>=2000~'21',d1$release_year>=1950~'second_half_20',d1$release_year<1950~'first_half_20')

Predict century2 using the descriptions. Give the accuracy and plot the confusion matrix table. (Notice that the codes for 8 should still work for this question)

d1<- d1%>% 
  mutate(target = century2) %>% 
  select(target, description) 

a <- recipe(target~description,
       data = d1) %>% 
  step_tokenize(description) %>% 
  step_tokenfilter(description, max_tokens = 50) %>% 
  step_tfidf(description) %>% 
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% 
  step_smote(target) %>% 
  prep()
d1 <- juice(a)

set.seed(2021)
splitIndex <- createDataPartition(d1$target, p = .10, 
                                  list = FALSE)
d1_train <- d1[ splitIndex,]
d1_test <- d1[-splitIndex,]

forest_ranger <- train(target~., data=d1_train, 
                        method = "ranger")

pred <- predict(forest_ranger, d1_test)

cm <- confusionMatrix(data = pred, reference = d1_test$target)
cm$overall[1]

## 0.9205532

Animal Reviews Data

We will study the Animal Crossing Data at Kaggle. The data file is user_review

7. Download the animal reviews data at this link. Read the data using read_tsv() function.

ac <- read_csv('user_reviews.csv')

8. Create a rating variable taking value good if the grade is greater than 7 and bad otherwise.

ac$rating <- ifelse(ac$grade>7,'good','bad')

9. Do the follows. Notice that the text information is in the text variable.

- Plot side-by-side word frequency by different categories of the `rating` variable
ac %>%

ac<- ac%>%

  select(target, text) 

a <- recipe(target~text,
       data = ac) %>% 
  step_tokenize(text) %>% 
  step_tokenfilter(text, max_tokens = 50) %>% 
  step_tfidf(text) %>% 
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% 
  step_smote(target) %>% 
  prep()
ac <- juice(a)
